      "content": [
        { "type": "title", "value": "Softening Particles" },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Cantonese is famous for its sentence-final particles. These small words don't have a meaning on their own but change the 'flavor' or mood of a sentence. Let's look at two essential ones: <strong>呀</strong> (aa3) and <strong>喇</strong> (laa3)."
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "好呀",
          "romanization": "hou2 aa3",
          "translation": "Okay / Good (Softened with 'aa3')"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "<strong>喇</strong> (laa3) indicates a change of state, like 'already' or 'now'. It's often used when you are about to do something or when something has just happened."
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "我去食飯喇",
          "romanization": "ngo5 heoi3 sik6 faan6 laa3",
          "translation": "I'm going to eat now"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "經理",
          "romanization": "ging1 lei5",
          "translation": "Manager"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "麻煩",
          "romanization": "maa4 faan4",
          "translation": "Trouble / Please (polite)"
        },
        {
          "type": "example",
          "cantonese": "簽名",
          "romanization": "cin1 ming4",
          "translation": "Sign signature"
        }
      ]
    },
    { "type": "reading", "exerciseId": "3.5.2" },
    { "type": "reading", "exerciseId": "3.5.6" },
    { "type": "reading", "exerciseId": "3.5.7" },
